✅ WEEK-12 – AWS Deployment Lab
1. DEPLOYMENT OF index.html USING EC2 INSTANCE
Step 1: Log in to AWS Academy

Open the AWS Academy course invitation email → Click Start

Sign in using student credentials

Click Modules

Scroll → Select Launch AWS Academy Lab – Learner Lab

Click Start Lab

Wait until the AWS button turns Green

Click on AWS to open the console

Step 2: Create an EC2 Instance

Search EC2 → Open

Click Launch Instance

Stage 1 – Instance Name

Enter name: ubuntu

Stage 2 – Select AMI

Choose: Ubuntu Server (Free Tier eligible)

Stage 3 – Architecture

Select: 64-bit (x86)

Stage 4 – Instance Type

Choose: t2.micro (1 vCPU, 1 GB RAM – Free Tier)

Stage 5 – Create Key Pair

Click Create new key pair

Give name (ex: MyKey)

Download .pem file

Save in a folder named AWS on Desktop

Stage 6 – Network Settings

Check all required inbound rules:

✔ HTTP (port 80)

✔ HTTPS (port 443)

✔ SSH (port 22)

Stage 7 – Storage

Default 8 GB → Keep as is

Stage 8 – Launch

Click Launch Instance

Step 3: Connect to the Instance

Go to Instances

Wait until both Status Checks (2/2) pass

Select the instance → Click Connect

Copy the SSH command

Step 4: Connect Using PowerShell/Git Bash
(a) Navigate to the key pair location
cd <path-to-your-pem-file>

(b) Run SSH command

Example:

ssh -i MyKey.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>

Step 5: Install Required Software
sudo apt update
sudo apt-get install docker.io
sudo apt install git
sudo apt install nano

Step 6: Create Web Application and Upload to GitHub
(a) Create index.html on your laptop
(b) Open Git Bash inside the folder → Run:
git init
git add .
git commit -m "first commit"

(c) Create GitHub Repository
(d) Push the code
git branch -M main
git remote add origin <repo-url>
git push -u origin main

Step 7: Clone the Repository on EC2
git clone <repo-url>
cd <folder-name>
ls

Step 8: Create Dockerfile on EC2
nano Dockerfile


Paste:

FROM nginx
COPY . /usr/share/nginx/html


Save:

Ctrl + O, Enter

Ctrl + X

Step 9: Build & Run Docker Image
Build image:
sudo docker build -t mywebapp .

Run container:
sudo docker run -d -p 80:80 mywebapp

Step 10: Test the Website

Go to EC2 → Copy Public IPv4 address

Open in browser:

http://<public-ip>


You should see your index.html webpage.

Step 11: Stop Container & Terminate Instance
sudo docker ps
sudo docker stop <container-id>


Then in AWS:

Select instance → Instance State → Terminate

After termination → End Lab

✅ END OF EXERCISE 1
2. MAVEN WEB PROJECT DEPLOYMENT ON AWS

This is similar but uses a Maven Web App.

Step 1: Start AWS Lab

Start lab → Open AWS console → EC2 → Launch Instance

Same EC2 creation steps as above (Ubuntu, t2.micro, key pair, network settings)

Step 2: Connect to Instance

Connect using SSH

Navigate to PEM file path

Run SSH command

Step 3: Install Required Software
sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker.io
sudo apt install git
sudo apt install maven

Step 4: Clone Maven Web Project

Go to your GitHub Maven repo

Copy HTTPS URL

On EC2:

git clone <repo-url>
cd <project-folder>

If the project is in master:

Switch branch to main:

git branch -M main
git pull

Step 5: Build Docker Image for Maven Web App

Create Dockerfile:

nano Dockerfile


Paste:

FROM tomcat:9
COPY target/*.war /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/


Save and exit.

Build image:
sudo docker build -t mymavenwebapp .

Run container:
sudo docker run -d -p 9090:8080 mymavenwebapp

Step 6: Configure Security Group

If webpage does not open:

Go to EC2 → Security Groups

Edit inbound rules

Add rule:

Port: 9090
Source: 0.0.0.0/0


Save

Now open:

http://<public-ip>:9090/<your-app-name>

Step 7: Stop and Terminate
sudo docker ps
sudo docker stop <container-id>


AWS:

Terminate instance

End Lab
